join Mark (Mark_half) right
[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/The_figure_turns_slowly.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
The figure turns slowly.
[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/Its_the_Principal.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
It's the Principal.
join Principal (Principal_half) center
[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/But_something_is_different_Their_expression_is_softer_more_contemplative.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
But something is different. Their expression is softer, more contemplative.
if {selected_character} == "celestine":
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/In_their_hand_they_hold_your_card.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
	In their hand, they hold her card.
	Principal: "Will you teach me one more lesson?" You wrote that.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/The_protagonists_eyes_widen_with_realization.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
	Celestine's eyes widen with realization.
	Celestine: B.C. Bernardino Cruz. Principal Bernardino Cruz.
	Celestine: It's been you all along.
	audio music "res://assets/audio/bg/chill3.mp3" [loop="true"]
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/Principal_B_C_smiles_gently.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
	Principal - B.C. - smiles gently.
	Principal: You've grown perceptive, Celestine. Yes. I am B.C.
	Mark: Wait, you... you've been leaving the cards? Guiding sis through all of this?
	Principal: I have. Though I suspect you have questions.
	Principal: Please, sit. This conversation has been long overdue.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/They_gesture_to_chairs_on_the_stage.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
	They gesture to chairs on the stage.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/The_protagonist_and_Mark_sit_the_protagonist_leaning_forward_intently.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
	Celestine and Mark sit, Celestine leaning forward intently.
	Celestine: Why? Why the mystery? Why guide me through cases instead of just teaching directly?
	Principal: Because direct teaching rarely transforms people, Celestine.
	Principal: You can tell a student that honesty matters. They'll nod and forget within a week.
	Principal: But if they experience the consequences of dishonesty, solve a case built on lies...
	Celestine: They internalize the lesson. They feel it.
	Principal: Exactly. Truth isn't just a concept to you anymore. It's something you've fought for.
	Celestine: But you didn't create the cases, did you? You didn't make Greg cheat or Ria take the fund.
	Principal: No. I would never manipulate students that way.
	Principal: Those choices were theirs alone, born from their own struggles and pressures.
	Principal: I simply observed. Watched human nature unfold as it always does.
	Principal: And when opportunities arose - moments where moral lessons could be learned - I left cards.
	Celestine: You guided me to solve cases I would have investigated anyway.
	Principal: And in solving them, you learned far more than just who committed which act.
	Principal: You learned about truth, responsibility, creativity, and wisdom.
else:
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/In_their_hand_they_hold_your_card.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
	In their hand, they hold his card.
	Principal: "Will you teach me one more lesson?" You wrote that.
	[voice path="res://assets/audio/voice/Chapter 5/c5s2/The_protagonists_eyes_widen_with_realization.mp3" volume="0.0" bus="Voice"]
